Job Tenure Over Time

Kimberly Seung Goulart

May 17, 2022

five Countries - UK, FR, DE, IT (includes the 4 Western European countries with the largest populations)

Average Tenure Over Time

I used both weights and multiplied them together - Post-stratification x Country In-Work population

Average Tenure Over Time by Gender

Average Tenure Over Time by Occupational Class

Models

Time (year) variable is treated as a continuous variable.

Controls Age, age squared, migrant dummy, country

Weights - post-stratification weights

mall1 <- lm(tenure ~ year*sex + age + + imm + occ_class, data = filter(five), weights = w5)
mall1plot <- plot_model(mall1, type = "pred", terms = c("year", "sex"))

mfr1 <- lm(tenure ~ year*sex + age + + imm + occ_class, data = filter(five, country=="FR"), weights = w4)
fr1plot <- plot_model(mfr1, type = "pred", terms = c("year", "sex"))

mde1 <- lm(tenure ~ year*sex + age + + imm + occ_class, data = filter(five, country=="DE"), weights = w4)
de1plot <- plot_model(mde1, type = "pred", terms = c("year", "sex"))

mit1 <- lm(tenure ~ year*sex + age + + imm + occ_class, data = filter(five, country=="IT"), weights = w4)
mit1plot <- plot_model(mit1, type = "pred", terms = c("year", "sex"))

mes1 <- lm(tenure ~ year*sex + age + + imm + occ_class, data = filter(five, country=="ES"), weights = w4)
mes1plot <- plot_model(mes1, type = "pred", terms = c("year", "sex"))

muk1 <- lm(tenure ~ year*sex + age + + imm + occ_class, data = filter(five, country=="UK"), weights = w4)
muk1plot <- plot_model(muk1, type = "pred", terms = c("year", "sex"))

ggarrange(fr1plot, de1plot, mit1plot, mes1plot, muk1plot, mall1plot)

five <-five %>% 
  mutate(pred = predict(m1, newdata = .))

five %>% select(tenure, pred) %>% pivot_longer(cols = everything()) %>% ggplot(aes(value, fill = name)) + geom_density(alpha = .5)
